 {"id": "franken_networkx-mwclqnone", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] max_weight_clique rejected weight=None; nx accepts and treats as cardinality", "description": "nx.max_weight_clique(weight=None) treats every node as having weight 1, so the algorithm returns a max-cardinality clique and the returned weight equals len(clique). The Rust binding rejected None with ``TypeError: argument weight: 'None' is not an instance of 'str'`` AND a Rust-side edge-attribute cache made in-place ``G.nodes[n]['weight'] = 1`` invisible to the Rust call (the raw algorithm still read the ORIGINAL weights). Delegate weight=None to nx for the cardinality-returning semantics. Default weight='weight' still hits the Rust fast path.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T23:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T23:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T23:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate weight=None to nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-swintf", "title": "REVIEW: [LOW] stoer_wagner returned float cut value for all-int weights", "description": "stoer_wagner with int-weighted inputs returned ``5.0`` where nx returned ``5`` (int). Python's 5 == 5.0 so equality tests pass, but isinstance(val, int) checks differ. Noted for potential future fix; not currently blocking.", "status": "open", "priority": 4, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T23:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T23:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-ikeck0", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] is_k_edge_connected accepted k<1 and returned True; nx raises ValueError", "description": "nx.is_k_edge_connected raises ``ValueError('k must be positive, not {k}')`` for k<1 (k=0 and k<0). The Rust binding accepted k=0 and returned True (vacuously), and also accepted negative k. Users doing is_k_edge_connected(G, k) with k computed from some expression that could be 0 would silently get True where nx raises an error. Added a Python-side guard that raises nx's exact ValueError for k<1.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-25T00:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-25T00:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-25T00:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Python-side k<1 guard", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
-{"id": "franken_networkx-composeedgeorder", "title": "REVIEW: [LOW] compose stored undirected edge as (1,0) where nx stores (0,1)", "description": "compose on two graphs with overlapping node 1 stored the resulting edge as (1, 0) where nx stored it as (0, 1). For undirected Graph the edge (0, 1) == (1, 0) logically, but the tuple order printed in edges(data=True) differs. Users comparing edge-list outputs via sorted() see a divergence. Minor cosmetic issue \u2014 queued for later.", "status": "in_progress", "priority": 4, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-25T00:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-25T01:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-composeedgeorder", "title": "REVIEW: [LOW] compose stored undirected edge as (1,0) where nx stores (0,1)", "description": "compose on two graphs with overlapping node 1 stored the resulting edge as (1, 0) where nx stored it as (0, 1). For undirected Graph the edge (0, 1) == (1, 0) logically, but the tuple order printed in edges(data=True) differs. Users comparing edge-list outputs via sorted() see a divergence. Minor cosmetic issue \u2014 queued for later.", "status": "closed", "priority": 4, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-25T00:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-25T01:10:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-25T01:10:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "compose now assembles outputs in Python in G-then-H order, preserving NetworkX undirected edge tuple orientation and H attribute precedence.", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-dijkignoreweight", "title": "REVIEW: [CRITICAL] single/multi/all_pairs_dijkstra ignored edge weights \u2014 returned hop-counts", "description": "The Rust _raw_single_source_dijkstra (and its multi_source and all_pairs variants) silently returned hop-count distances on weighted graphs. On path_graph(5) with every edge weight=1.5, fnx.single_source_dijkstra_path_length(G, 0) returned {0:0, 1:1.0, 2:2.0, 3:3.0, 4:4.0} where nx correctly returns {0:0, 1:1.5, 2:3.0, 3:4.5, 4:6.0}. Downstream algorithms like group_closeness_centrality showed wildly wrong values (0.320 vs 0.470 on karate). _should_delegate_dijkstra_to_networkx only triggered for callable weights and negative weights, missing positive non-unit weights. Added _graph_has_nonunit_weight helper that returns True when any edge carries weight != 1 at the named attr. Wired into single_source_dijkstra, single_source_dijkstra_path, single_source_dijkstra_path_length, multi_source_dijkstra, all_pairs_dijkstra, all_pairs_dijkstra_path, and all_pairs_dijkstra_path_length. Unweighted fast path preserved.", "status": "closed", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-25T00:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-25T00:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-25T00:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate non-unit-weight inputs to nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-ivgnode", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] interval_graph used integer node labels 0..n-1; nx uses the interval tuples as labels", "description": "nx.interval_graph uses the input interval (a, b) tuples themselves as node labels, so callers access e.g. ``G.nodes[(1, 3)]`` and edges are ``((1, 3), (2, 5))`` tuples. fnx stored nodes as integers 0..n-1, so edges were ``(0, 1)`` etc. and ``G.nodes[(1, 3)]`` raised KeyError. Rewrote interval_graph to store each interval tuple as a node; also added validation (length-2 interval, lower bound first) matching nx's contract. Updated tests/python/test_parity_comprehensive.py's test_interval_graph to assert against the tuple-keyed contract.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-25T01:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-25T01:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-25T01:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Use tuple node labels matching nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-bfignoreweight", "title": "REVIEW: [CRITICAL] bellman_ford family silently ignored edge weights (same class as dijkstra bug)", "description": "single_source_bellman_ford, single_source_bellman_ford_path_length, all_pairs_bellman_ford_path*, and _raw_single_source_bellman_ford all returned hop-count distances on weighted input instead of weighted distances \u2014 the same bug class as br-dijkignoreweight. On path_graph(5) with every edge weight=2.5, fnx returned {0:0, 1:1.0, 2:2.0, 3:3.0, 4:4.0} where nx returns {0:0, 1:2.5, 2:5.0, 3:7.5, 4:10.0}. Added _graph_has_nonunit_weight check to all five wrappers + bidirectional_dijkstra; delegate to nx when any edge has non-unit weight. Verified all now match nx exactly.", "status": "closed", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-25T01:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-25T01:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-25T01:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate weighted inputs to nx across BF family", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
